844	Iter-031's source-object iso (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_top_sourceIso}) feeds into the Ext-level transport: the natural iso of source objects induces a $k$-linear isomorphism on the resulting $\Ext$ groups, by pre- and post-composition with $\Ext.\mathtt{mk\_0}$ on the iso's hom and inverse. The classical lemmas $\Ext.\mathtt{mk\_0\_comp\_mk\_0}$ ($(\mathtt{mk\_0}\,f).\mathrm{comp}\,(\mathtt{mk\_0}\,g) = \mathtt{mk\_0}\,(f \circ g)$) and $\Ext.\mathtt{mk\_0\_id\_comp}$ collapse the round-trip composition through the iso's identity equations $\alpha.\mathtt{hom}\circ\alpha.\mathtt{inv} = \mathtt{id}$ and $\alpha.\mathtt{inv}\circ\alpha.\mathtt{hom} = \mathtt{id}$, witnessing the round-trip.
